Using Lagrange Multipliers, we set up the following system of equations:
\begin{align*}
&f(x,y,z) = \sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}\\
&g(x,y,z) = xyz - 1\\
&\nabla f = \lambda \nabla g
\end{align*}

Taking partial derivatives, we get:
\begin{align*}
\nabla f &= \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}}\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix}\\
\nabla g &= \begin{pmatrix} yz \\ xz \\ xy \end{pmatrix}
\end{align*}

Setting $\nabla f = \lambda \nabla g$, we get:
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}}\begin{pmatrix} x \\ y \\ z \end{pmatrix} &= \lambda \begin{pmatrix} yz \\ xz \\ xy \end{pmatrix}\\
\Rightarrow \quad \frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}} &= \lambda yz\\
\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}} &= \lambda xz\\
\frac{z}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}} &= \lambda xy
\end{align*}

Squaring and adding the equations, we get:
\[\frac{x^2+y^2+z^2}{x^2y^2z^2} = \lambda^2 (x^2+y^2+z^2)\]

Since $x^2+y^2+z^2 \neq 0$, we can divide both sides by $x^2+y^2+z^2$ to get:
\[\frac{1}{x^2y^2z^2} = \lambda^2\]

Rearranging, we get:
\[\lambda = \frac{1}{\sqrt{(xyz)^2}} = \frac{1}{|xyz|}\]

Substituting this back into the equation $\nabla f = \lambda \nabla g$, we get:
\begin{align*}
\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}} &= \frac{yz}{|xyz|}\\
\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}} &= \frac{xz}{|xyz|}\\
\frac{z}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}} &= \frac{xy}{|xyz|}
\end{align*}

Since $xyz=1$, we can simplify the equations to:
\begin{align*}
\frac{x}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}} &= yz\\
\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}} &= xz\\
\frac{z}{\sqrt{x^2+y^2+z^2}} &= xy
\end{align*}

Squaring and adding the equations, we get:
\[x^2y^2+y^2z^2+z^2x^2 = (xyz)^2 = 1\]

