Let $p$ be the fixed perimeter of the sector. Then we have $p = 2r + r\theta,$ so $r = \frac{p}{2+\theta}.$ The area of the sector is $\frac{r^2 \theta}{2} = \frac{p^2 \theta}{4(2+\theta)^2}.$ To maximize this expression, we can take its derivative with respect to $\theta$ and set it equal to 0:

\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{d\theta} \left( \frac{p^2 \theta}{4(2+\theta)^2} \right) &= \frac{p^2}{4(2+\theta)^2} - \frac{p^2 \theta}{2(2+\theta)^3} \\
&= \frac{p^2(4-\theta)}{4(2+\theta)^3} = 0.
\end{align*}

This happens when $\theta = 4,$ so that is the value that maximizes the area of the circular sector. Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{4}$ radians.
